### Splatting 3D Gaussian Points

The 3D Gaussian point is formally defined as

\[G(\mathbf{x}\mid\mathbf{\mu},\mathbf{\Sigma})=e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{\mu})^{T}\mathbf{\Sigma} ^{-1}(\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{\mu})} \tag{6}\]

In the given equation, \(\mathbf{\mu}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\) represents the spatial mean and \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\in\mathbb{R}^{3\times 3}\) denotes the covariance matrix. To ensure validity throughout the optimization process, the covariance matrix \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\) is decomposed into a scaling matrix \(\mathbf{S}\) and a rotation matrix \(\mathbf{R}\) as follows:

\[\mathbf{\Sigma}=\mathbf{RSS}^{\top}\mathbf{R}^{\top} \tag{7}\]

During the rendering process, the 3D Gaussians are projected onto a 2D plane. With the intrinsic matrix \(\mathbf{K}\) and extrinsic matrix \(\mathbf{T}\), the 2D mean \(\mathbf{\mu}^{\prime}\) and covariance \(\mathbf{\Sigma}^{\prime}\) are defined as follows:

\[\mathbf{\mu}^{\prime}=\mathbf{K}[\mathbf{\mu},1]^{\top},\quad\mathbf{\Sigma}^{\prime}=\mathbf{JT} \mathbf{\Sigma}\mathbf{T}^{\top}\mathbf{J}^{\top} \tag{8}\]

Here, \(\mathbf{J}\) represents the Jacobian of the affine approximation of the projective transformation. Each Gaussian is associated with an opacity value o and a view-dependent color \(\mathbf{c}\), determined by a set of spherical harmonics coefficients. The pixel color \(\mathbf{C}\) is computed by performing alpha-blending on the sorted 2D Gaussians, starting from the front and progressing toward the back.

\[\mathbf{C}=\sum_{i\in N}T_{i}G_{i}\left(\mathbf{u}\mid\mathbf{\mu}^{\prime},\mathbf{\Sigma}^{ \prime}\right)\sigma_{i}\mathbf{c}_{i} \tag{9}\]

where \(T_{i}=\prod_{j=1}^{i-1}\left(1-G_{i}\left(\mathbf{u}\mid\mathbf{\mu}^{\prime},\mathbf{ \Sigma}^{\prime}\right)\sigma_{i}\right)\).

